# Prod Lockdown — workspace-side enforcement

This is the **single most important operational document** in the repo. Without
the steps here, every other safeguard (validators, PR review, branch protection,
the in-app SHA check) can be bypassed by anyone with workspace write access.

The pipeline catches *mistakes*. This document is what catches *deliberate
bypasses* — the case Mark and Juliana run into when someone "just deploys
real quick to prod" and breaks it.

---

## The three layers of enforcement

| Layer | Where | Who configures | What it blocks |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1. Pipeline | `.github/workflows/` | repo author | Hardcoded values, empty downgrades, missing grants |
| 2. GitHub | repo settings | `scripts/setup_branch_protection.py` | Direct push to main, unreviewed merges, force-push |
| 3. **Workspace** | Databricks workspace permissions | **this document** | Manual `bundle deploy`, workspace-UI uploads, ad hoc Lakebase ALTERs |

Layers 1 and 2 are software. Layer 3 is admin work. **All three must be in
place.** Skipping layer 3 makes the others largely ceremonial.

---

## One-time per workspace — admin checklist

### Apps

```sh
# 1. Identify the CI service principal.
CI_SP=<service-principal-client-id>

# 2. Remove human CAN_MANAGE from every existing prod app.
for app in $(databricks apps list --output json | jq -r '.[].name'); do
    # leave only the CI SP with CAN_MANAGE
    databricks permissions set apps "$app" \
        --json "{
          \"access_control_list\": [
            {\"service_principal_name\": \"$CI_SP\", \"permission_level\": \"CAN_MANAGE\"}
          ]
        }"
done

# 3. Block humans from creating new apps directly (must go through CI).
# Workspace setting: "Apps -> Create" entitlement -> grant only to CI SP group.
```

### Lakebase

```sh
INSTANCE={{.lakebase_instance_name}}

# Owner = CI SP. Humans get CAN_USE at most.
databricks postgres update-instance "$INSTANCE" \
  --owner-service-principal-id "$CI_SP"

databricks permissions set lakebase-instance "$INSTANCE" \
  --json "{
    \"access_control_list\": [
      {\"service_principal_name\": \"$CI_SP\", \"permission_level\": \"CAN_MANAGE\"}
    ]
  }"
```

### Workspace files

Humans must not write under the Git Folder path that the app deploys from.
This prevents in-place edits in the workspace UI.

```sh
# Replace with your actual Git Folder path
GIT_FOLDER=/Workspace/Repos/hss-platform/{{.app_name}}

databricks workspace set-permissions "$GIT_FOLDER" \
  --json "{
    \"access_control_list\": [
      {\"service_principal_name\": \"$CI_SP\", \"permission_level\": \"CAN_MANAGE\"},
      {\"group_name\":              \"hss-app-readers\", \"permission_level\": \"CAN_READ\"}
    ]
  }"
```

### Audit alert (the real-time tripwire)

Create a Lakeflow alert on `system.access.audit` that pages the platform team
whenever someone other than the CI SP touches an App or Lakebase resource:

```sql
-- Save as a Lakeflow alert with severity = high, recipient = platform team
SELECT
  event_time,
  user_identity.email AS who,
  action_name,
  request_params:name AS target,
  request_params
FROM system.access.audit
WHERE event_date >= current_date() - INTERVAL 1 DAY
  AND service_name IN ('apps', 'postgres')
  AND action_name IN (
    'updateApp', 'deployApp', 'restartApp',
    'updatePostgresInstance', 'updatePostgresBranch', 'deletePostgresBranch'
  )
  AND user_identity.email NOT IN (
    '<ci-sp-email>',
    '<platform-admin-email>'
  )
ORDER BY event_time DESC;
```

When this alert fires you have **two pieces of evidence**: who tried to
bypass (from the audit row) and whether they succeeded (the app's in-process
self-check will have killed the app if so).

---

## Verifying the lockdown is in place

After completing the steps above, the `hss-app audit` CLI (when shipped)
will check each of these and flag any drift. Until then, verify manually
once per quarter:

```sh
# Should return ONLY the CI SP for every prod app:
databricks apps list --output json | \
  jq -r '.[].name' | \
  while read app; do
    echo "=== $app ==="
    databricks permissions get apps "$app" \
      --output json | jq '.access_control_list'
  done

# Should show owner = CI SP:
databricks postgres get-instance {{.lakebase_instance_name}} | jq .owner
```

---

## Why each layer matters

| Bypass attempt | What stops it |
|---|---|
| `databricks bundle deploy -t prod` from laptop | Workspace permission (layer 3) — human lacks CAN_MANAGE on prod app |
| Workspace-UI file edit | Workspace permission (layer 3) — human lacks write on Git Folder |
| Force push to `main` | GitHub branch protection (layer 2) |
| Direct commit to `main` | GitHub branch protection (layer 2) — requires PR |
| PR merged without review | GitHub CODEOWNERS (layer 2) |
| PR with hardcoded values | Validator in PR + deploy gate (layer 1) |
| Migration with empty `downgrade()` | Validator AST check (layer 1) |
| App deployed manually but with valid code | In-app `EXPECTED_GIT_SHA` self-check refuses to start |
| Manual Lakebase ALTER on prod | Lakebase ownership = CI SP (layer 3) + audit alert |

If any column in this table doesn't have an entry, that's a gap. Right now
the table is complete only after a workspace admin completes this document's
checklist.
